Using SSql LanguageTo use the SSql language, start by creating a .SSql file. In this file, you can write SSql queries and data analysis tasks. Hereâ€™s a simple example:
1. Connect StatementEstablish a connection to a MySQL database using the CONNECT statement with a JDBC connection string, username, and password.
Before all operations, you must first use this statement to establish a connection to the database
CONNECT(&#39;jdbc:mysql:&#x2F;&#x2F;localhost:3306&#x2F;northwind&#39;,&#39;username&#39;,&#39;password&#39;)

2. Query StatementRetrieve all records from the orders table using the SELECT statement:
&#x2F;&#x2F; Query Statement
SELECT * FROM orders

3. Statistic StatementGenerate a bar chart with a title, X and Y labels, and data based on a query:
sqlCopy codeSTATS CHART BAR &#123;
	Title: &quot;ShipVia&quot;;
	XLabel: &quot;Count&quot;;
	YLabel: &quot;Y&quot;;
	Data: (SELECT orders.ShipVia, SUM(orderdetails.UnitPrice * orderdetails.Quantity * (1 - orderdetails.Discount)) FROM orders JOIN orderdetails ON orders.OrderID &#x3D; orderdetails.OrderID  BY orders.ShipVia);
&#125;

4. VariableDeclarationStore the result of a query in a variable for reuse:
VAR data4ShipVia &#x3D; (SELECT orders.ShipVia, SUM(orderdetails.UnitPrice * orderdetails.Quantity * (1 - orderdetails.Discount)) FROM orders JOIN orderdetails ON orders.OrderID &#x3D; orderdetails.OrderID  BY orders.ShipVia)

5. Statistic Statement with VariableGenerate bar and line charts using the data stored in a variable:
sqlCopy codeSTATS CHART BAR &#123;
	Title: &quot;ShipVia&quot;;
	XLabel: &quot;Count&quot;;
	YLabel: &quot;Y&quot;;
	Data: (data4ShipVia);
&#125;

STATS CHART LINE &#123;
	Title: &quot;ShipVia&quot;;
	XLabel: &quot;Count&quot;;
	YLabel: &quot;Y&quot;;
	Data: (data4ShipVia);
&#125;



6. Data CleaningPerform data cleaning operations on the products table:

Find duplicates:

sqlCopy codeSTATS CLEAN &#123;
	Table: &quot;products&quot;
	Column: &quot;UnitPrice&quot;
	Function: FIND_DUPLICATES
&#125;


Find missing values:

sqlCopy codeSTATS CLEAN &#123;
	Table: &quot;products&quot;
	Column: &quot;UnitPrice&quot;
	Function: FIND_MISSING_VALUES
&#125;


Find missing values and fill with the mean:

sqlCopy codeSTATS CLEAN &#123;
	Table: &quot;products&quot;
	Column: &quot;UnitPrice&quot;
	Function: FIND_MISSING_VALUES
	Solution: FILL_IN_MEAN
&#125;

7. Check StatementsPerform various checks on customers and products:

Check a customerâ€™s billing information:

sqlCopy codeCHECK Customer &#123;
	ID: &quot;ALFKI&quot;
	Type: BillAll
&#125;

CHECK Customer &#123;
	ID: &quot;ALFKI&quot;
	Type: Bill
	Date: 1994-07-15 to 1995-07-15
&#125;


Check product information and sales:

sqlCopy codeCHECK Product &#123;
	ID: &quot;3&quot;
	Type: ProductInfo
&#125;

CHECK Product &#123;
	Type: TopSale
	Date: 1996-07-15 to 2000-07-15
	Limit: 1
&#125;

CHECK Product &#123;
	CategoryName: &quot;Beverages&quot;
	Type: GroupCategory
&#125;

These use cases provide a solid understanding of the various capabilities of the SSql language and how to use them in practice.
